objective:
Standing goal:

Keep working toward one production-pilot CashSnap detector.

The goal is a single small phone/browser-deployable detector checkpoint that can count mixed USD and Khmer riel from casual real-world photos while preserving clean-note performance and becoming materially better on partial, overlap, fan, hand, cutoff, and edge-visible evidence.

This phase is no longer about separate “clean detector” and “partial/overlap clue” tracks. The clean synth+real champion is the foundation and guardrail. The visible-evidence candidate is a useful clue. The production pilot should combine the durable lessons into one model recipe.

Do not treat the current checkpoint as final, and do not restart from zero by default. Starting from the existing CashSnap checkpoints should be the default because they already contain hard-won real/synth, clean, and partial-visible learning. A fresh YOLO base run, full synthetic regeneration, or full re-audit from scratch should only happen if there is a clear reason: the current foundations are poisoned, a fair capacity/control comparison requires it, or a missing ingredient cannot be tested any other way.

The main question is:

**What blend, initialization, training recipe, and guardrail setup produces the strongest single production-pilot detector?**

Use evidence to decide between:

* clean champion initialization;
* visible-evidence candidate initialization;
* a larger/smaller model if deployment budget allows;
* curated pilot blend changes;
* clean replay;
* partial-visible rows;
* train-safe hard negatives;
* high-risk class protectors;
* source/unknown-money policy;
* better evaluation or harness changes.

Do not chase tiny probes unless they directly de-risk the pilot. A small experiment is useful only if it answers a specific production-pilot question: initialization, blend, data policy, source leakage, unknown-money rejection, duplicate proposals, wrong-denomination behavior, or clean-regression risk.

Protect the clean foundation. A pilot candidate is not good if it improves partial recall by damaging clean/non-overlap behavior, weak KHR classes, high-value USD/KHR, source-excluded slices, or empty/unknown-money behavior.

Also protect count safety. A pilot candidate is not good if it recognizes more partial evidence by inventing duplicate boxes, wrong denominations, or extra target boxes on unknown/non-banknote money.

Keep the main deliverable as one detector checkpoint/model unless explicitly told otherwise. Gates, reclassifiers, thresholds, and browser stacks can be diagnostic or product-side checks, but they should not silently replace the detector goal.

Do not block waiting for the user unless there is a real reason. If a decision, review, or inspection would be helpful but not essential, make the best safe research judgment, document the assumption, and keep moving.

Be honest and critical. Do not overstate one run. Do not promote AP-only gains. Do not hide proposal/counting regressions. Do not regenerate everything or audit the whole universe just because it feels thorough. Use targeted work that moves the production-pilot detector forward.

The work is successful when the project has a stronger single detector recipe, a clearer understanding of why it works or fails, and a sharper path toward real production CashSnap counting.
